01:07:32.730 --> 01:07:34.790
assets and paid off all
the debts, that's

01:07:34.790 --> 01:07:36.100
what would be left.

01:07:36.100 --> 01:07:38.620
So, you divide that by the
number of shares and you can

01:07:38.620 --> 01:07:42.070
get an estimate of the
value of a share.

01:07:42.070 --> 01:07:43.300
But I say an estimate.

01:07:43.300 --> 01:07:46.790
It's not the same as
the market value.

01:07:46.790 --> 01:07:50.890
In 2010, there were
1.4 billion shares

01:07:50.890 --> 01:07:53.880
outstanding in Xerox.

01:07:53.880 --> 01:07:57.130
The price per share
of a Xerox common

01:07:57.130 --> 01:08:01.810
share in 2010 was $11.80.

01:08:01.810 --> 01:08:04.770
So, if I multiply the number
of shares by the price per

01:08:04.770 --> 01:08:11.680
share, the market cap for
Xerox is $16.4 billion.

01:08:11.680 --> 01:08:14.319
Compare that with the
shareholders'

01:08:14.319 --> 01:08:18.310
equity of $11.9 billion.

01:08:18.310 --> 01:08:21.910
So, the company is worth more
than its shareholders equity.

01:08:21.910 --> 01:08:24.760
And you might ask, why
would that be?

01:08:24.760 --> 01:08:26.090
OK?

01:08:26.090 --> 01:08:30.880
Well, I think the answer is, you
wouldn't buy this company

01:08:30.880 --> 01:08:32.620
to shut it down.

01:08:32.620 --> 01:08:36.790
You could buy the company for
$16 billion and then shut it

01:08:36.790 --> 01:08:40.319
down, sell off all the assets,
pay off all the debts, and

01:08:40.319 --> 01:08:42.500
you'd have $11 billion.

01:08:42.500 --> 01:08:47.649
So, that's a sign of Anne
Mulcahy's success.

01:08:47.649 --> 01:08:50.410
Her company is not going
to be shut down.

01:08:50.410 --> 01:08:54.850
If the stock price falls below
the shareholders' equity, it

01:08:54.850 --> 01:08:57.779
becomes at risk for
being shut down.

01:08:57.779 --> 01:09:01.330
Somebody buys the company and
