I sell it.

01:09:17.040 --> 01:09:18.680
I get $11.9 billion.

01:09:18.680 --> 01:09:20.160
I've doubled my money.

01:09:20.160 --> 01:09:22.620
All right.

01:09:22.620 --> 01:09:25.580
Now, a company can sell for less
than the shareholders'

01:09:25.580 --> 01:09:28.229
equity, because the
shareholders' equity is kind

01:09:28.229 --> 01:09:29.670
of a funny number.

01:09:29.670 --> 01:09:32.500
It's also called stockholders'
equity by some

01:09:32.500 --> 01:09:35.399
people, same thing.

01:09:35.399 --> 01:09:36.910
It's a funny number,
because it involves

01:09:36.910 --> 01:09:37.899
all kinds of estimates.

01:09:37.899 --> 01:09:40.340
And if you really try to sell
that real estate for what it

01:09:40.340 --> 01:09:42.270
says here, you might
find problems.

01:09:42.270 --> 01:09:49.780
So, the market capitalization
can follow below shareholders'

01:09:49.780 --> 01:09:53.030
equity, but probably
not too far below.

01:09:53.030 --> 01:09:56.830
And this is what worries
boards and CEOs.

01:09:56.830 --> 01:09:59.810
They watch their stock price
every day and they've got in

01:09:59.810 --> 01:10:02.170
their mind that shareholders'
equity.

01:10:02.170 --> 01:10:05.180
And if the stock is falling
below that, then they're in

01:10:05.180 --> 01:10:06.280
danger of liquidation.

01:10:06.280 --> 01:10:08.240
So, they worry.

01:10:08.240 --> 01:10:12.820
And that's why every morning, if
you are a CEO, if you're a

01:10:12.820 --> 01:10:16.560
CEO of a public company, you
will be watching your market

01:10:16.560 --> 01:10:20.000
cap every day and comparing that
with shareholders equity.

