01:14:44.090 --> 01:14:45.300
They're much bigger.

01:14:45.300 --> 01:14:48.380
But is that the way to
measure Microsoft?

01:14:48.380 --> 01:14:50.250
This is a measure
of the value.

01:14:50.250 --> 01:14:52.990
It's really the liquidation
value of Microsoft.

01:14:52.990 --> 01:14:59.360
So, you could imagine buying
Microsoft and then selling all

01:14:59.360 --> 01:15:02.820
those assets, shutting it
down, firing everybody.

01:15:02.820 --> 01:15:05.140
Would that be a smart
thing to do?

01:15:05.140 --> 01:15:06.380
You fire everybody.

01:15:06.380 --> 01:15:08.380
You sell the Redmond campus.

01:15:08.380 --> 01:15:10.430
You sell all of their
computers.

01:15:10.430 --> 01:15:13.180
And what do you end up
with? $48 billion.

01:15:13.180 --> 01:15:18.020
Well, let's compare that with
the market cap of Microsoft.

01:15:18.020 --> 01:15:24.060
They have 8,497 million shares
outstanding, and the price per

01:15:24.060 --> 01:15:27.750
share at the end of
2010 was $26.

01:15:27.750 --> 01:15:30.595
So, the market cap
is $221 billion.

01:15:30.595 --> 01:15:34.880
So, that's over five times their
shareholders equity.

01:15:34.880 --> 01:15:37.520
That means that they have
some other value.

01:15:37.520 --> 01:15:40.450
I think I'm running
out of time.

01:15:40.450 --> 01:15:44.640
It's interesting what happens
in the world.

01:15:44.640 --> 01:15:46.190
I'll stop with this.

01:15:46.190 --> 01:15:51.040
This is the price per
share of Microsoft.

01:15:51.040 --> 01:15:52.870
I should disclose.

01:15:52.870 --> 01:15:54.770
I'm now a shareholder.

01:15:54.770 --> 01:15:58.920
I wish I were a shareholder
back then.

01:15:58.920 --> 01:16:00.160
Nobody believed it.

01:16:00.160 --> 01:16:01.830
This only goes back
to '86, but the

01:16:01.830 --> 01:16:03.220
company maybe was private.

01:16:03.220 --> 01:16:04.610
I forget when it went public.

01:16:04.610 --> 01:16:05.970
So, we don't have prices
[addition: before '86],

01:16:05.970 --> 01:16:07.820
but we have prices in '86.

01:16:07.820 --> 01:16:13.450
It really had a run until 2000,
and then something broke

01:16:13.450 --> 01:16:15.940
with Microsoft as well.

01:16:15.940 --> 01:16:17.580
It looks a little bit like
Xerox, doesn't it?

01:16:17.580 --> 01:16:19.710
I think it was the end of
the high tech bubble.

01:16:19.710 --> 01:16:23.430
This was a bubble in
tech prices, and

01:16:23.430 --> 01:16:25.430
Microsoft rode the bubble.

01:16:25.430 --> 01:16:27.690
But it's still doing
very well.

01:16:27.690 --> 01:16:29.440
It's just not going up lately.

01:16:29.440 --> 01:16:30.720
Anyway, this is an example.

